ArrayList Methods in Java (Detailed Guide)

ArrayList provides a rich set of methods to manage elements: adding, removing, updating, searching, and iterating.

1. Adding Elements
add()
list.add("Apple");          // adds to the end
list.add(1, "Banana");      // adds at specific index
addAll()
list.addAll(anotherList);          // adds all elements
list.addAll(1, anotherList);       // adds at index

👉 Useful for merging lists.

2. Accessing Elements
get()
String item = list.get(0);
fast operation (O(1))
throws IndexOutOfBoundsException if index is invalid
3. Updating Elements
set()
list.set(1, "Mango");
replaces element at index
does NOT change list size
4. Removing Elements
remove()
list.remove(0);        // remove by index
list.remove("Apple");  // remove by value
removeAll()
list.removeAll(anotherList);

👉 removes all matching elements

removeIf() (Java 8+)
list.removeIf(item -> item.startsWith("A"));

👉 uses lambda (functional style)

clear()
list.clear(); // removes everything
5. Searching and Checking
contains()
list.contains("Apple");
indexOf() / lastIndexOf()
list.indexOf("Apple");
list.lastIndexOf("Apple");
returns index or -1 if not found
isEmpty()
list.isEmpty();
6. Size and Capacity
size()
int size = list.size();
ensureCapacity() (rarely used)
list.ensureCapacity(100);

👉 pre-allocates memory for performance

trimToSize()
list.trimToSize();

👉 reduces memory to actual size

7. Iterating Over ArrayList
for-each loop
for (String item : list) {
    System.out.println(item);
}
for loop
for (int i = 0; i < list.size(); i++) {
    System.out.println(list.get(i));
}
forEach() (Java 8+)
list.forEach(item -> System.out.println(item));
Iterator
Iterator<String> it = list.iterator();

while (it.hasNext()) {
    System.out.println(it.next());
}
8. Sorting
sort()
list.sort(String::compareTo);

Or with lambda:

list.sort((a, b) -> a.compareTo(b));
9. Converting ArrayList
toArray()
Object[] array = list.toArray();
toArray with type
String[] array = list.toArray(new String[0]);
10. Other Useful Methods
equals()
list1.equals(list2);

👉 checks if two lists are equal

clone()
ArrayList<String> copy = (ArrayList<String>) list.clone();
subList()
List<String> sub = list.subList(0, 2);

👉 returns a portion of the list

Important Notes
ArrayList allows duplicates
allows null values
maintains insertion order
not synchronized (not thread-safe)
Performance Summary
Operation	Complexity
get()	O(1)
add() (end)	O(1)
add/remove (middle)	O(n)
search (contains)	O(n)
Final Summary

ArrayList methods allow you to:

add → add(), addAll()
access → get()
update → set()
remove → remove(), removeIf(), clear()
search → contains(), indexOf()
iterate → loops, forEach(), Iterator
sort → sort()
